07021nam a22011055i 9780520918573DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209185737 a10.1525/97805209185732doi  a(DE-B1597)544147  a(OCoLC)1149429038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHT166b.M2464 1998eb 7aARC0050002bisacsh04a307.1/2/0922100aMaking the Invisible Visible :bA Multicultural Planning History /ced. by Leonie Sandercock.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (268 p.) :b14 figs., 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Critical Human Geography ;v200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I • Historical Practices -- t1. Spaces of Insurgent Citizenship -- t2. Feminist and Multicultural Perspectives on Preservation Planning -- t3. Regional Blocs, Regional Planning, and the Blues Epistemology in the Lower Mississippi Delta -- t4. Indigenous Planning -- t5. Remember, Stonewall Was a Riot -- tPART II • Textual and Theoretical Practices -- t6. Knowing Different Cities -- t7. City Planning for Girls -- t8. Tropics of Planning Discourse -- t9. Subversive Histories -- t10. Racial Inequality and Empowerment -- t11. Afraid/Not -- t12. The Poem of Male Desires -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of planning is much more, according to these authors, than the recorded progress of planning as a discipline and a profession. These essays counter the mainstream narrative of rational, scientific development with alternative histories that reveal hitherto invisible planning practices and agendas. While the official story of planning celebrates the state and its traditions of city building and regional development, these stories focus on previously unacknowledged actors and the noir side of planning.Through a variety of critical lenses—feminist, postmodern, and postcolonial—the essays examine a broad range of histories relevant to the preservation and planning professions. Some contributors uncover indigenous planning traditions that have been erased from the record: African American and Native American traditions, for example. Other contributors explore new themes: themes of gendered spaces and racist practices, of planning as an ordering tool, a kind of spatial police, of "bodies, cities, and social order" (influenced by Foucault, Lefebvre, and others), and of resistance.This scrutiny of the class, race, gender, ethnic, or ideological biases of ideas and practices inherent in the notion of planning as a modernist social technology clearly points to the inadequacy of modernist planning histories. Making the Invisible Visible redefines planning as the regulation of the physicality, sociality, and spatiality of the city. Its histories provide the foundation of a new, alternative planning paradigm for the multicultural cities of the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCity planningxHistoryvCross-cultural studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aafrican american traditions.  acalifornia studies in critical human geography.  acity building.  acity planning.  aclass.  aethnicity.  afeminism.  afeminist theory.  afoucault.  agender.  agendered spaces.  ageography.  ahistory of planning.  ahuman geography.  aindigenous planning.  ainvisible planning practices.  alefebvre.  anative american traditions.  aordering tool.  aplanning as a discipline.  aplanning as a profession.  apostcolonial.  apostcolonialism.  apostmodernism.  apostmodernity.  arace.  arac